commit_message:
Enable 'python_version=='2.6' for futures and enum34

Enable futures for 2.6 this until the discussion around oslo.messaging
need for this (and its support for 2.6) and its planned usage of the futurist
library for the liberty release.

Also some of the current oslo libraries (taskflow) still support 2.6
for the short-term (until a few other reviews merge) so we need to enable
its usage there still for enum34.

This is also breaking the futurist, automaton, gate and the taskflow check
gates as those are still on 2.6 (this may change soon).

Soon the following will make that less relevant (but these haven't merged
yet):

- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/193349/
- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/193354/
- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/194860/

Change-Id: I9256563a6c2cc455043f0d61cd27b033d37302ef

commit_message:
Add required to cidr field for 'Add Subnet'

When adding subnet for a network, if no cidr is specified, the workflow
will not be able to process to next without any message to inform the
user that the cidr is required. This patch adds required attribute to
cidr field.

Change-Id: If6daee1fe949dc0d4524e35e0323a7f0cfd7c190
Closes-bug: #1467810

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Use string exception casting everywhere

Instead of the deprecated "message" member access,
casting to a string invokes the __str__ method of the exception
that is wired to return the message

Added a test of the failure cases of IpRouteCommand::delete_gateway
because they were missing

Running unit and functional tests locally no longer shows the warning
reported in the bug.

Change-Id: Ia79f526aa973ece1145615d65349f860aa3fd465
Closes-Bug: #1466542

commit_message:
install_rally.sh: permit absolute paths for sqlite db name

If the SQLite database name (--db-name) starts with a /, assume that
it's an absolute path, instead of being relative to
$RALLY_DATABASE_DIR (which is not configurable).

Change-Id: Ief9485f4dd7f8d2becdb2ebfd78cf29b411aece7

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I99ca8682a3a6cc2558c61e512a52bdde21d1b32a

commit_message:
Override opportunistic database tests to PyMySQL

Set the OS_TEST_DBAPI_ADMIN_CONNECTION override variable so that
oslo.db opportunistic detection will know to use PyMySQL until
I12b32dc097a121bd43991bc38dd4d289b65e86c1 makes it the default
behavior.

This change removes previous code[1] enabling PyMySQL use.

[1] Ic5c1d12ab75443e1cc290a7447eeb4b452b4a9dd

Change-Id: Ic39feee0248f2ffabdba26f3779ab40a8f3838e6
Co-Authored-By: Victor Sergeyev <vsergeyev@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Cedric Brandily <zzelle@gmail.com>

commit_message:
[Heat] create-snapshot-restore-delete stack scenario

The patch adds rally scenario that tests the following
sequence of actions for Heat:
1) create stack
2) create stack snapshot
3) restore stack from snapshot
4) delete stack

Change-Id: I5fb46be697c9ae1450b323a4e632ab13d7600998

commit_message:
Extend default setenv instead of replacing it in tox.ini

Some tox jobs[1] define their own setenv without extending/referencing
default setenv, it disallows to define environment variables shared by
all jobs. This change updates previous jobs[1] in order to extend
instead of replacing default setenv and enable global environement
variables (used in daughter change).

One remark, this change sets VIRTUAL_ENV environment variable in updated
jobs[1] but it has no effect on them.

[1] (dsvm-)functional, (dsvm-)fullstack and api jobs

Closes-Bug: #1468059
Change-Id: I99184f7375571fb8569a24ba04ae267108f5da08

commit_message:
Bulk move methods to ipam_backend_mixin.py

ipam_backend_mixin contains methods common for both backends:
pluggable and non-pluggable, so moving methods to make them accessible
by backends.
Next methods were moved from db_base_plugin_v2.py to
ipam_backend_mixin.py:
- _validate_subnet_cidr
- _validate_network_subnetpools
- _allocate_pools_for_subnet
- _save_subnet

This commit moves methods without any internal changes.
All future changes and decomposition of these methods will be handled in
next commits.

Partially-Implements: blueprint neutron-ipam

Change-Id: I1ec786754467fc9039d2276f084f1bceaab15635

commit_message:
Fix SR-IOV mech driver to set port status to down when agent is required

SR-IOV mech driver has 2 modes agent and agent-less. Currently in both
modes port status are active. This patch update the port status to down
when using agent mode. This will allow the SR-IOV agent to get port
update notification and apply its additional functionality
when launching vm.

Co-Authored-By: Berezovsky Irena <irenab.dev@gmail.com>

Closes-Bug: #1464186

Change-Id: Ibd9b31b4f2393b8732253d5cbfd36e8b5614860d

commit_message:
Add IPset cleanup script

This will aid in removing stale IPsets when we change the prefix
used in creating IPset names.

Change-Id: Ia9ff79c34bd4c9124ec8663a8f616ded4f389f62
Partial-Bug: #1444201

commit_message:
Set tag ACLs for more networking libraries

Both octavia and dragonflow are libraries used by neutron, so set their
ACLs to let the library-release team manage tagging.

Change-Id: I3448927decc636503b7ce9e0d454ed3b4b29f2b3

Between the time that instance A is associated with fixed IP X and the

commit_message:
Reduce window for allocate_fixed_ip / release_fixed_ip race in nova-net

There is a race during allocate_fixed_ip where a new instance, B, is
associated with a fixed IP, X, which was previously associated with
instance A that is being deallocated.

Between the time that instance A is associated with fixed IP X and the
time that it's VIF is allocated, and fip.allocated = True in the DB, the
dhcpagent callback hits release_fixed_ip for the fixed IP X from when
instance A was deallocating.

release_fixed_ip checks to see if the instance is allocated and if not
it disassociates the instance, which was associated with new instance B.

This leads to get_instance_nw_info() not building anything since there
are no fixed IPs associated with instance A in the database, so
eventually anything needing to do networking with instance A, like
assocating a floating IP, fails.

To narrow the race, we do the VIF allocation before associating the
fixed IP to the new instance. This does not completely fix the bug, but
it's a tactical change that we can backport to stable branches while
working on the longer-term fix which is going to involve network RPC API
changes to release_fixed_ip().

Note that test_vpn_allocate_fixed_ip_no_network_id is removed since it
no longer works and arguably was testing the DB API in the wrong place,
so a new test is added to test_db_api for the same coverage.

Partial-Bug: #1249065

Change-Id: I8cf5483982085da57ee470fa2753b0d0aebc12b3
(cherry picked from commit 3736c120cbeacbc4349efbda99e279cddfb5f09e)

commit_message:
Remove version from setup.cfg

Pbr is calculating versions on it's own based on git tags.
So we don't need to specify by hands in setup.cfg version

Change-Id: Ia5b4859b662d98facf3c211ae813962bd07feef0

commit_message:
Display all versions info in versions controller

This patch enables the "versions controller" or "/" resource to display
information relevant to all the versions of the Barbican API (which is
only v1 at the moment). This is done in the same fashion Keystone
displays it, and it has the purpose of enabling more automatic discovery
as described in the blueprint.

Accessing the root resource with the "build" query parameter, such as:

    $ curl http://localhost:9311/?build

will display the build information.

On the other hand, this introduces the V1Controller, which is now the
root controller (which requires authentication) for Barbican.

Accessing the "/v1" resource will display the version information in the
way it's required by keystone.

The json-home implementation is left for a subsequent CR.

Partially implements blueprint fix-version-api
Change-Id: Ie7e706adcf1b5d74f64776b888a06638247b4e87

commit_message:
Sprinkle in Horizon translations for Zanata

Building on work landed in II3bfb188c8b0c0e65f22d7edc30721b163f084fff,
add support for pushing source documents of Horizon into Zanata.
This has also necessitated adding support for parsing and adding
rules for create-zanata-xml.py.

As a drive-by correct some incorrect docstrings in ZanataUtils, split
some ludicrously long lines calling create-zanata-xml.py, and correct
usage of an undefined variable in setup_django_openstack_auth.

Change-Id: Id7a2c82e979d1f878022b4982f51ef4ef06ecf4b

commit_message:
Fix errors when enabling SSL for apache

keystone_ssl_enabled is used to determine whether or not to configure
apache to use SSL. Currently when this variable is set to true the
apache SSL module is not enabled.

This commit adds a task to enable/disable the SSL module based on the
variable keystone_ssl_enabled.

The keystone-httpd.conf template causes a formatting error. This commit
fixes the error so that additional whitespace is no longer added before
SSLEngine.

Change-Id: I1415e5822684af12e1a1dd8a306e708e8931fa38
Closes-bug: #1466827

commit_message:
Use fixture to register command line option

Use the config fixture to register the command line option in
test_fetch_func_args_database instead of registering it directly. This
ensures that the option is de-registered at the end of the test, and
should help with the intermittent failure in
unit.common.test_service.TestCommonService.test_prepare_service.

Change-Id: I58f09dd6fa3057af1ff55766e4f67e1a4604ea38

commit_message:
Disable THP in MongoDB elements.

Make sure to disable Linux kernel feature transparent huge pages,
it will affect greatly both memory usage and latency in a negative way.
See: http://docs.mongodb.org/manual/tutorial/transparent-huge-pages/

Partially Implements: blueprint mongodb-database
Change-Id: If6bf4cea056cd9f865811966c8428eaf4c5c2cfe

commit_message:
Update botocore client and use cloned novaclient for functional tests

Since botocore 1.0.0 is released we make ec2api functional tests
to be compatible with it.

Previously used novaclient modification (v14 of
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/152569/) is too obsolete. It is not
compatible with modern oslo libraries. Current version of this
modification (v34) is obsolete as well.

The proposed solution is to use a separate novaclient repository, which
can be maintained independently of community. Until microversions are
not supported by novaclient upstream.

Change-Id: I75e1bbcd81678a56a0940b696cfa5dbc2c159cc6

commit_message:
Dogfood things for unit tests

So it turns out we weren't actually using ostestr for running the
os-testr unit tests. We probably should use the test runner runner
wrapper we're developing to run the unit tests for the test runner
runner wrapper and the other utilities in the package.

Change-Id: I88af9104352163f2412c2a3cbaf6c88d0a937988

(1 comment)

I'm good with this change.

What I'm not sure about, is whether/how we should be updating existing/approved specs. Since this spec landed in kilo, someone reading this may think that this is the behavior in kilo, but it isn't.

This is just a general question wrt any spec updates. Eg, don't know if we should keep the original and put a separate paragraph for 'In Liberty, ...'"}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2015-06-24 15:47:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Firstly, changing a previously approved and completed spec should only be done for cosmetic cleanup or fixing errors -- whereas this is changing the definition of the feature, and should be done in a new spec.

Secondly, I disagree with the premise here: "is only intended for human consumption"

Node names are entirely usable on the command line, and thus may be used by any automation tools (eg, bash, ansible) when calling ironic.'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-06-24 15:52:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

@Devananda. Thanks for clarifying. So this is really a -2, since a new spec is required for this change.

@Chris. It might be worth mentioning that nova has taken this route.'}, {'account_id': 11748, 'date': '2015-06-24 16:29:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-24 16:32:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

- gate-ironic-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/38/195138/3/check/gate-ironic-specs-python27/f4c0a32/ : SUCCESS in 2m 15s'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-06-24 17:28:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(3 comments)

Thanks Chris.

Now I am wondering how we handle this.

logical names were added in microversion 1.5. For requests with < 1.5, we return HTTP 406 status.

with this change, we're bumping the microversion to 1.F:

For requests < 1.5, we'll still return HTTP 306 status.

For requests 1.5 <= x <= 1.F: do we A. allow freeform names, or B. only allow 'valid' hostnames, and return HTTP 406 status for invalid hostnames?

I'm thinking it might be (B), but hoping it is (A)."}, {'account_id': 11748, 'date': '2015-06-24 18:10:32.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Per Devananda, we're keeping logical names hostnames."}]

[{'created': '2015-06-18 20:16:37.000000000', 'message': 'Capture and gracefully handle failed interface attach/detach API calls.

When the rug notices a discrepancy between the interfaces on a router VM and
the ports that neutron knows about, it attempts to resolve them via Nova
`interface-attach` and `interface-detach` API calls.  If these calls fail,
however, the state machine falls into an endless loop of -> Configure -> Replug
-> Configure -> Replug.  In the event that VM hot plugging/unplugging fails, we
should fall back to recreating the VM.

Change-Id: Ic49cd21376d024f4834523dabc5c320946dbd012
Fixes-bug: #1466623
'}]
commit_message:
Capture and gracefully handle failed interface attach/detach API calls.

When the rug notices a discrepancy between the interfaces on a router VM and
the ports that neutron knows about, it attempts to resolve them via Nova
`interface-attach` and `interface-detach` API calls.  If these calls fail,
however, the state machine falls into an endless loop of -> Configure -> Replug
-> Configure -> Replug.  In the event that VM hot plugging/unplugging fails, we
should fall back to recreating the VM.

Change-Id: Ic49cd21376d024f4834523dabc5c320946dbd012
Fixes-bug: #1466623

commit_message:
Add read/write_affinity settings for Swift

Allow the setting of read/write_affinity and write_affinity_node_count
on a per proxy_host basis.

This allows the deployer to set preferences for which region to
read/write to, which can increase the efficiency of a multi-region
swift cluster.

Sample swift.yml has been updated, as well as the aio swift.yml to
ensure these settings are setup as part of the gate, but this shouldn't
change the functionality of swift at all (since there is only 1 region).

Change-Id: I95b456672f419fcc331d6739ce259b022d350472
Closes-Bug: #1415172

commit_message:
Control list of enabled services for tempest job.

This patch moves the list of enabled services into the local job
config so that we can more easily update it.  This list is the same as
what was in project-config with "n-obj" added.  One of the test
failures was
tempest.thirdparty.boto.test_ec2_instance_run.InstanceRunTest failing
when trying to create an S3 bucket, so I think turning this service
on will resolve that.

Change-Id: Ie9669381f0a1d5a695d998ab8453eb2427d39926
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Add global endpoint_type_proto options

This allows you to set the endpoint-type protocol globally for all
services, e.g. internaluri can be http, and publicuri can be https.

You will no longer have to specify it per service, although those
settings already exist and have not changed.

This patch changes no functionality for existing installs or deployments
and the values are defaulted to be the same as before, but allows these
values to be adjusted on a per-endpoint type basis.

Change-Id: I4854216726491f6ea4e265694e702f980fddc5a6
Closes-Bug: #1399383

commit_message:
Do not run requirements check on keystonemiddleware kilo branch

Due to a mismatch in requirements that prevents us from increasing the
minimums, keystonemiddleware for kilo cannot have the requirements check
run against it or it fails. See: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/173972/
for more info.

Change-Id: I5dcbab958f7dd2fe4c675e48620919d9b84e69ca
related-bug: #1463988

commit_message:
MySQL manager refactor

There are a number of forks of MySQL that differ to varying degrees.
We propose to create a class structure for MySQL-derived
datastores to avoid duplication of code dealing with features
and capabilities shared in common.

It is expected that the lessons learned from this effort will be
applicable to future efforts to provide differentiation for systems
such as MongoDB and PostgreSQL.

Change-Id: I56fe640a7f81f9a7a6906580e6484ddfbf84e677
Implements: blueprint mysql-manager-refactor

surrounding flow to also REVERT.  This is because the Retry controller
is returning REVERT rather than REVERT_ALL.

commit_message:
Fix revert on ERROR/Exception

Failure on a sub flow that is being Retry'd is not forcing the
surrounding flow to also REVERT.  This is because the Retry controller
is returning REVERT rather than REVERT_ALL.

Change-Id: Ib70fd37a0349c5cf89f73a2ca2334400b87bff56
Closes-Bug: 1452958

commit_message:
Ensure we 'join' on the timer watchdog thread

This object is just another thread and its cancel method
does not join on itself, so we should make sure that we do
to avoid leaving threads lying around.

Change-Id: I37e3170b58627dee93513ec222f9a55001389dad

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: Id86fa35bc81d9d24211d8553ac2ef9e91949ba7a

commit_message:
Expose RUG API port as a config option

This removes the hard-coding of the RUG REST API port and exposes
it as a new config option.  The devstack code is updated to set this
and point horizon at the correct port.

Change-Id: I8bf4832ea5e96c0a4a2221c3a04d1fb52376e387

commit_message:
Do not store session db in tmp directory

This commit prevents situation, when after machine reboot manage.py syncdb is needed
to recreate a database.

The db location changed to murano /opt/stack/murano-dashboard in murano devstack script.
Documentation also was updated.

Change-Id: I9603c13d5ce170d516acea208c33f92570f04c96
Closes-Bug: #1464215

This looks like a reasonable approach, however os-collect-config only merges group:os-apply-config data, and the hiera element is likely relying on that merging, so defining a new group orc-hiera-datafiles would mean no merging.

How about deploy_stdout echoed the 'id' of the deployment entry instead the hash of all hieradata? The 'id' is the derived config id, so it will _always_ change if anything changes in the config or deployment resource.

This also has the advantage of being a general solution for all os-apply-config deployments which want to do similar digest thingys in the templates."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-06-11 07:17:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

[{'created': '2015-06-10 17:56:11.000000000', 'message': 'Add orc-hiera-datafiles signalling

Currently signalling via 99-refresh-completed only uses the legacy
curl data payload (e.g that for CFN compatible WaitConditions),
but now we're using it exclusively for signalling SoftwareDeployment
resources, which support a different payload, including deploy_stdout
which is accessible via a resource attribute.

So add support a new orc-hiera-datafiles group, which calculates
a hash of the hieradata files and sends it back as part of the
deploy_stdout.  Also send a better stdout than "null" for the existing
os-apply-config deployment group.

This means we can derive a hash of the hieradata files deployed via e.g:

get_attr: [ControllerDeployment, deploy_stdout]

Partial-Bug: #1463092

Returning a payload for deploy_stdout containing the derived config ID

commit_message:
Return derived config id when signalling deployments

Currently signalling via 99-refresh-completed only uses the legacy
curl data payload (e.g that for CFN compatible WaitConditions),
but now we're using it exclusively for signalling SoftwareDeployment
resources, which support a different payload, including deploy_stdout
which is accessible via a resource attribute.

Returning a payload for deploy_stdout containing the derived config ID
is potentially useful as it changes whenever the SoftwareConfig or any
inputs change, thus can be used as a unique identifier for dependent
resources which need to be re-triggered when some config is reapplied,
for example puppet manifests with a dependency on hieradata applied
via a SoftwareDeployment.

get_attr: [ControllerDeployment, deploy_stdout]

Partial-Bug: #1463092
Change-Id: Ic62b6303795f70f3b9ace46731a21d1c0e7fe6c7

commit_message:
Make puppet-applying *Post resources depend on hieradata

When you do a stack-update which affects, e.g ControllerDeployment
such that some value in hieradata is updated (for example changing
the "Debug" parameter to True), we only write the hieradata file and
don't reapply the manifests.

So we introduce a dependency on the deploy_stdout values from all
hieradata applying configs, such that the manifests will be re-applied
on update if the data is changed.

This requires https://review.openstack.org/#/c/190282/ so that
99-refresh-completed will return the derived config ID as part of the
deploy_stdout payload.

Closes-Bug: #1463092
Change-Id: I1175248c3236d0c42e37d062afce550efce8aadc

Make lbaas API test jobs voting again

The lbaas api job was made non-voting because it was testing the wrong
neutron, which has been fixed. Both jobs have been running experimental and
then check queue stably, and tested that they are testing the expected repo:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/188166/

commit_message:
Disable Floating IP features if Neutron router is disabled

If the config option 'enable_router' is set to False,
Floating IP features are disabled when Neutron is enabled.
It does not affect when Neutron is disabled.

It also adds unit tests for api.network.servers_update_addresses
which is affected by this change.

Completes blueprint hide-router-panel-by-config
Closes-Bug: #1292022

Conflicts:
	doc/source/topics/settings.rst
	openstack_dashboard/api/neutron.py
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/access_and_security/tests.py
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/instances/tests.py
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/overview/tests.py
	openstack_dashboard/usage/base.py
	openstack_dashboard/usage/quotas.py

Change-Id: Ib63c6a0e7bb5661d4a60d10a1722fdad978b50bb

'}, {'created': '2015-06-24 14:35:00.000000000', 'message': "Add a new ModelBase.items() method

This change is required to port applications using oslo.db to Python 3.
The iteritems() method of Python 2 dictionaries was removed in Python 3
(renamed to items()). Currently, it's not possible to replace
obj.iteritems() with six.iteritems(obj) or obj.items() for oslo.db
objects.

Nova has a function calling obj.iteritems(), the function gets oslo.db
objects and dictionaries. On Python 3, dictionaries have no iteritems()
method, whereas oslo.db objects have no items() method. This change
allows to write obj.items() which works on Python 2 and Python 3, on
dictionaries and oslo.db objects.

On Python 3, the ModelBase.iteritems() method now returns an iterator
instead of a list. The behaviour on Python 2 is unchanged to not break
backward compatibility.

Change-Id: Ibd4f454183c2bd3465539c3e572fa23208975bdb

commit_message:
Add a new ModelBase.items() method

This change is required to port applications using oslo.db to Python 3.
The iteritems() method of Python 2 dictionaries was removed in Python 3
(renamed to items()). Currently, it's not possible to replace
obj.iteritems() with six.iteritems(obj) or obj.items() for oslo.db
objects.

Nova has a function calling obj.iteritems(), the function gets oslo.db
objects and dictionaries. On Python 3, dictionaries have no iteritems()
method, whereas oslo.db objects have no items() method. This change
allows to write obj.items() which works on Python 2 and Python 3, on
dictionaries and oslo.db objects.

Change-Id: Ibd4f454183c2bd3465539c3e572fa23208975bdb

There is a race during allocate_fixed_ip where a new instance, B, is
associated with a fixed IP, X, which was previously associated with
instance A that is being deallocated.

Between the time that instance A is associated with fixed IP X and the
time that it's VIF is allocated, and fip.allocated = True in the DB, the
dhcpagent callback hits release_fixed_ip for the fixed IP X from when
instance A was deallocating.

release_fixed_ip checks to see if the instance is allocated and if not
it disassociates the instance, which was associated with new instance B.

This leads to get_instance_nw_info() not building anything since there
are no fixed IPs associated with instance A in the database, so
eventually anything needing to do networking with instance A, like
assocating a floating IP, fails.

To narrow the race, we do the VIF allocation before associating the
fixed IP to the new instance. This does not completely fix the bug, but
it's a tactical change that we can backport to stable branches while
working on the longer-term fix which is going to involve network RPC API
changes to release_fixed_ip().

Note that test_vpn_allocate_fixed_ip_no_network_id is removed since it
no longer works and arguably was testing the DB API in the wrong place,
so a new test is added to test_db_api for the same coverage.

Partial-Bug: #1249065

"}]
commit_message:
Reduce window for allocate_fixed_ip / release_fixed_ip race in nova-net

There is a race during allocate_fixed_ip where a new instance, B, is
associated with a fixed IP, X, which was previously associated with
instance A that is being deallocated.

Between the time that instance A is associated with fixed IP X and the
time that it's VIF is allocated, and fip.allocated = True in the DB, the
dhcpagent callback hits release_fixed_ip for the fixed IP X from when
instance A was deallocating.

release_fixed_ip checks to see if the instance is allocated and if not
it disassociates the instance, which was associated with new instance B.

This leads to get_instance_nw_info() not building anything since there
are no fixed IPs associated with instance A in the database, so
eventually anything needing to do networking with instance A, like
assocating a floating IP, fails.

To narrow the race, we do the VIF allocation before associating the
fixed IP to the new instance. This does not completely fix the bug, but
it's a tactical change that we can backport to stable branches while
working on the longer-term fix which is going to involve network RPC API
changes to release_fixed_ip().

Note that test_vpn_allocate_fixed_ip_no_network_id is removed since it
no longer works and arguably was testing the DB API in the wrong place,
so a new test is added to test_db_api for the same coverage.

Partial-Bug: #1249065

Change-Id: I8cf5483982085da57ee470fa2753b0d0aebc12b3

commit_message:
Add a build script + build_image tox env

This adds a little script to call DIB to build an appliance with the
currently checked out code, and adds a tox target to call that.
This'll mostly be used by the jenkins bot when doing image builds as
a post build job.

Change-Id: I636cd5c37884c5bf9bfe1051716e6c3790ed0165

commit_message:
Add the rule of separate plugin for Nova REST API in devref

This patch adds the describe how to separate plugin when adding new
resource or some extended for existed resource.

Change-Id: Ib356aa9df0a3b85580ea2869ce4d043a6850967a

commit_message:
[elasticsearch] default trait type to string

when trait mapping is not found, get_events for es backend will
assume the last known type that was mapped. this patch changes that
so it will default to text type if a mapping is not found.

Change-Id: I5c5b263f0160726034dfca59d70d2a6a32585cb5
Closes-Bug: #1453919
(cherry picked from commit 906c72fc216a108cd949faf94fc2a2adda014a9b)

commit_message:
Get rid of openstack/common package

* use oslo graduated modules, delete openstack/common package since there
  is no dependency on oslo-incubator modules now.
* delete openstack-common.conf for the reason above.
* update project requirements automatically.

Change-Id: I80610cbfe7fd54263c8a2d9178ec9a2498c91899
Closes-Bug: #1459188

commit_message:
Edits to dev guide, juno guide, and kilo guide

Dev Guide:
- Added notes to assist whoever is using the guide for when they run into an error
that I previously encountered (repeatedly). 
- Added apt-get update as first step

Sample Config File:
- Added a sample pool configuration
- Removed pool backend configs
- Created config file specific to kilo and juno
- Removed backends=bind9


Juno Guide:
- Corrected a few typos in the guide for juno
- Updated mysql commands
- Changed config file name

Kilo Guide:
- Created a duplicate of the ubuntu-dev guide and modified it to work specifically for the kilo branch

Change-Id: I9343852b2834affd0fe6c1e3f85c0f25002a0ee7

Support use admin creds in KeystoneClientV3

which configures in magnum.conf

commit_message:
Properly establish SNAT rules for VMs that have no Floating IP.

This fixes a bug whereby VMs *without* a Floating IP can not reach other VMs
via *their* Floating IP.

Fixes-bug: #1467562
Change-Id: Iad2076beecb86dd27fe2630d4c2fbe9e8a0a97a4

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I3c0c969c388c19bce85336ba304f42b5df181652

commit_message:
Initial commit of swift backend

Enables:
* Message expiry
* Message listing
* Batch operations by message ID
* queue creation

Todo:

* Claims
* Sharding queues
* Use swift vendor prefixes to enable multitenancy

Change-Id: I547bc7b2a013eded3dcdfa332079404d228545d0
Depends-On: I692c35dcf217bede557ac463b2388f9a60d96c79

commit_message:
Disable apparmor for libvirtd.

Our devstack integration currently installs ovs from source and breaks
apparmor.  Disable apparmor for libvirtd, which is where we see the
problems.

Change-Id: I23827eeb2acc8ec22071094dd21fa6807806769c
Co-authored-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

More javelin unit tests

Improving test coverage of Javelin by covering more resources:

* routers: create/destroy
* secgroups: create/destroy
* subnets: destroy

commit_message:
Fix the way q-agent-cleanup executes shell processes

Shell commands are executed via subprocess.Popen(). Currently the
status of process is tracked by wait() method which results in deadlocks
when output is large enough (tens of kB). The correct way is to use
communicate() method.

Partial-bug 1436414

commit_message:
Remove openrc/admin-token usage in q-agent-cleanup.py

Removes the openrc/admin-token deps in q-agent-cleanup.py. Instead it will
read the neutron service credentials out of neutron.conf. This has the
advantage that it must be up to date for neutron to function so if the
credential is modified it will have to be updated by the administrator.

Related-bug: #1347542
Closes-bug: #1396594

Conflicts:
	deployment/puppet/cluster/files/q-agent-cleanup.py
	utils/jenkins/python-test-requirements.txt

Change-Id: Iee0968a079deacef24b56f34e9314b0ebecad0ae

commit_message:
Backport packaging of OCF scripts from 6.1 to 6.0-updates

We need a way to deliver fixes for OCF scripts in MOS 6.0 deployments as a part of maintenance updates.
To achieve that OCF scripts should be packaged in the same way as they are in 6.1.

Change-Id: I511a23b8a8523a811cd2d2b6a418977ae9e979ba
Closes-bug: #1465771

commit_message:
Add optional machine conversion into a pydot graph

Both ironic and taskflow share this same code to convert
their state machines into a pydot graph which then gets
converted into SVG to form:

- http://docs.openstack.org/developer/taskflow/states.html
- http://docs.openstack.org/developer/ironic/dev/states.html

So instead of duplicating it, provide a useful helper function
that both (and others) can share to produce a dot/graphviz pretty
diagram from a state machine.

Change-Id: I218740910163a1ca2587d706edc55852af1c0c74

fwaas/lbaas: create the required DB tables

FWaaS and LBaaS require additional tables in the neutron DB to be
entirely functional.

commit_message:
Add virt-driver CPU thread pinning

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/virt-driver-cpu-pinning

Resubmit the thread policy aspect of the 'virt-driver-cpu-pinning'
spec, which was not implemented in Kilo.

Change-Id: Iec6635bd0e24716bbc366c3faabf888d09700b56
Blueprint: virt-driver-cpu-pinning

commit_message:
Auto generate minimal environment variables doc

This script will generate the minimal-environment-variables doc
based on the what each services has in the check_required_var field.
Anytime that field is changed run this script and commit the changes.
Since Neutron is a thick container, the script will get a few duplicates
in the neutron-agents field.  When Neutron is thinned out, this script
will function normally.

Closes-bug: #1459347

Co-Authored-By: Lon Hohberger <lhh@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I1ba6bd5148af12cacfd872591b3c7b84a8dccba2

commit_message:
Add Heat resource support

This patch adds support to listing resources from a Heat stack. To the
make the test case happy, test_proxy_base is slightly modified. Also,
when testing proxy methods, some mock calls (decorators) are introduced.

The functional test in previous patchsets is pulled out and left as a
TODO item. Will need to fix some related resource.find() logic before
making functional tests work.

Change-Id: Ibc553b0927e019cd03dc49ec16b5e41e4526bde3

commit_message:
Change fat neutron container into thin containers

Key difference here is the ip_wrapper.py file. This file and docker 1.7
allow for the network namespaces to be created in the host mount
namespace and propogated into the containers.

Co-Authored-By: Paul Bourke <paul.bourke@oracle.com>
Change-Id: I73bcd1c97bbaf742af883dbf281a8d76aff8aebf

commit_message:
Add support to inherited project role grant calls

Once inherited project role grant calls are
implemented on python-keystoneclient,
python-openstackclient also should support such
calls.
This patch add such support as well as its
related tests.

Co-Authored-By: Raildo Mascena <raildo@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: Id72670be8640e5c6e2490a6ef849e9ec3493b1a9
Implements: blueprint hierarchical-multitenancy

commit_message:
Remove attempts to close success message in tests

This commit removes attempts to close a success message, because horizon code
may hide and remove the message before tests are able to close it. This
could trigger false negatives from time to time.
It's harmless to ignore success the message as long as it is present on the page.

Change-Id: I660d174493cade75fcab6a8f5b7f6214dd188589
Related-Bug: #1466332

commit_message:
Remove openstack.common modules

This patch removes unused openstack.common modules and replaces
versionutils with oslo_log.versionutils.
This fixes the gate issue partly, by removing openstack.common.log which
in some cases could override CONF object in horizon.

Change-Id: I94972726129c256d53377320b8b632afb56b8906
Closes-Bug: #1466332

commit_message:
Use monotonic lib. to avoid finding monotonic time function

That library already does this same/equivalent search and
ensures that a monotonically increasing time is made available
so we can just avoid looking around for it ourselves.

Change-Id: I2b5c69430d75a095f6743c10e2d9281f7d9120e0

commit_message:
Port Event based Subnet binding and ARP responder install

Change the Subnet binding and ARP responder to be dynamically (only
where needed) installed as response to port status form the switch ,
Until this patch we looped on all the subnets and routers on all port
status ignoring the actual port configured on the switch

Change-Id: I59d03ffc52a9b47eeebe4f467a1d41fe1844c8ae

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I797d23fc5283e1951f8f75eecc23830b1ae0de69

commit_message:
Implement external physical bridge mapping in linuxbridge

In some deployment scenario, it is not allowed to remove system
ethernet configuration from physical interface to newly-created
physical bridge by neutron due to some IT regulations.

End-users require to take advantage of the pre-existed(user-defined)
physical bridge to connect tap devices.

Change-Id: Ic76907a852f8e85d47fdc4286cf86ac57076ce34

commit_message:
DO NOT MERGE: Example of using VIF plug script

This patch is a sample usage of the proposed VIF_PLUGIN_SCRIPT
mechanism. This field will be populated by a Neutron mechanism driver
and refers to driver specific script that will be called from the
virtualization driver when the system is ready to connect the guest to a
L2 network.

Change-Id: I3b5daadc9bba446cd6c644f1052b05cb77111b19

commit_message:
Make l3 agent prefix delegation pluggable

Unlocks the prefix delegation feature so that developers may create
drivers for other prefix delegation services in the future.
Operators can select the driver via the new configuration option
"pd_dhcp_driver".

DocImpact
Change-Id: I2a9342c14825458f814d1ec9fa5a992b7f6e13f7
Implements: blueprint ipv6-prefix-delegation

Before we opt in maintaining our own PD implementation written in python that uses magic numbers to access different parts of packet headers, I would like everyone to ask themselves whether the community is capable of implementing and maintaining for years protocol intensive on-the-wire level code. We are good at integrating stuff, but I'm not sure the community has enough eyes and minds capable of maintaining security critical piece of code like that PD daemon injected into tenant networks.

I don't see particular reason not to follow the example of other features we have in neutron that consistently rely on external daemons that do one thing and do it right."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-04-03 11:59:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Note that if we are concerned that e.g. dibbler is not available in distribution repositories and that blocks gate testing, then the right thing would be to reach those distributions to package it.

For Fedora and EPEL7, I did the work, and it will be in F20+ and EPEL7 repos in a week or so, so we'll be able to gate against it: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1206639"}, {'account_id': 4656, 'date': '2015-04-06 14:03:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

I think we should extract a part of this patch that removes the direct dependency on Dibbler, and introduces the driver configuration.

That's a good piece of work that should get merged, while we figure out the best way to move forward with the other parts of this patch which creates a native python client."}, {'account_id': 6637, 'date': '2015-04-23 13:41:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-23 14:45:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified-1

'}, {'created': '2015-03-13 18:01:37.000000000', 'message': 'Add an internal DHCPv6 client for Prefix Delegation

In order to use prefix delegation without the use of an external service
such as Dibbler this patch adds a small agent dedicated to handling
DHCPv6 Prefix Delegation which can run alongside the L3 Agent.

The API for PD drivers in the L3 Agent is slightly changed to make it
as pluggable as possible.

This patch adds several new configuration options which firstly allow the
Prefix Delegation driver to be set in the config file along with the
ability to customise some parts of the DHCPv6 conversation.

The agent can be started using the "neutron-dhcpv6-client" command and
must run with elevated privileges.

The L3 Agent communicates with this service via Unix sockets, using the
PDManager we implement.

Co-Authored-By: Bradley Jones <jones.bradley@me.com>

Change-Id: Ic3849b4f0ad64804b642d00daadb9f265f2a7b62
Implements: blueprint ipv6-prefix-delegation

such as Dibbler this patch adds a small agent dedicated to handling
DHCPv6 Prefix Delegation which can run alongside the L3 Agent.

The API for PD in the L3 Agent is slightly changed to make it support
different drivers for PD. Drivers must implement a PDManager object
with enable, disable, get_prefix, and get_sync_data functions.

This patch adds several new configuration options which allows the
driver for PD to be set in the config file along with the ability to
customise some parts of the DHCPv6 conversation for the internal driver.

The agent can be started using the "neutron-dhcpv6-client" command and
must run with elevated privileges.

The L3 Agent communicates with this service via Unix sockets, using the
PDManager we implement in the driver.

commit_message:
Add an internal DHCPv6 agent for Prefix Delegation

In order to use prefix delegation without the use of an external service
such as Dibbler this patch adds a small agent dedicated to handling
DHCPv6 Prefix Delegation which can run alongside the L3 Agent.

The agent can be started using the "neutron-pd-agent" command and
must run with elevated privileges. The L3 Agent communicates with this
service via a driver which can be enabled in the neutron settings file
by setting pd_dhcp_driver to neutron_pd_agent.

In order to configure the neutron PD agent the "pd_socket_loc" and
"pd_interface" configuration options have been added.

Co-Authored-By: Bradley Jones <jones.bradley@me.com>

DocImpact
Change-Id: Ic3849b4f0ad64804b642d00daadb9f265f2a7b62
Implements: blueprint neutron-ipv6-prefix-delegation-service

I'd encourage you to take this issue to the mailing list to raise it's visibility.  Filing a bug is also necessary so we can track it for release purposes.  

Regarding the performance implications of this change, it would be helpful if you would describe (preferably on the ml) the testing and associated setup you performed to validate your approach."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-05-26 12:53:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

I think the idea of switching to cast is fine.  However, it's not clear to me why utils.async() is needed since it seems oslo.messaging is doing message processing in a thread already."}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2015-05-27 00:49:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Russel: The eventlet Oslo messaging executor uses eventlet.pool.spawn, which uses greenthread.spawn internally. The RPC endpoint code runs in that greenthread. My code then runs that code via eventlet.spawn_n, which seems to fasten execution during simple local benchmarking. I'll admit I'm not 100% sure why but it was a 10% improvement when making the OVS agent plug 40 ports. It was quite consistent."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-05-27 04:05:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

The only difference is that spawn() tracks the result (return value or exception).  spawn_n doesn't give you any way to track it.  The oslo.messaging is very intentionally doing it this way to keep track of greenthreads currently processing messages.  This patch breaks what it's doing.

You mention it's a 10% improvement, but how much time are we talking?  Is that a 10% overall improvement, or just a targeted bit of code?  Just curious what the impact is ..."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-05-27 04:08:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Before I said I thought the patch was OK, but I actually misunderstood what this was doing.  I do *not* think it makes sense to keep using call() here.  If what you really want is performance and async behavior, this should really just be cast().  If the code is not currently resilient to the message not making it or being processed correctly, it's broken in either case."}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2015-05-27 08:42:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-06-24 15:05:36.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

This review is > 4 weeks without comment, and failed Jenkins the last time it was checked. We are abandoning this for now. Feel free to reactivate the review by pressing the restore button and leaving a 'recheck' comment to get fresh test results."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-06-24 15:05:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-12 20:54:09.000000000', 'message': "Return early from RPC call handlers with no return value

Oslo messaging reminder:
cast: Send and forget. You only get an ACK from the messaging server,
not from the intended recipient.
call: Block until the recipient sends a return value or exception.

Agents often use call and not cast when updating about certain events,
even though the recipient (Neutron server in this case) has no return
value on the RPC endpoint (Think OVS agent update_device_up). The intention
is to notify that something happened, so naturally you don't care about
a return value. In the cases I observed there is no error handling in
the agents either.

Since there's no need to wait for a response or to see if the server
successfully updates whatever it is that it needs to update, we have
two choices:
a) Switch from call to cast in these cases
b) It can still be preferable to use call and not cast to get a
   stronger delivery guarantee. Perhaps you'd still want to bug out
   if the recipient is down or otherwise non-responsive.

Note: The oslo.notify API uses call underneath so that's not a real
      alternative.

In this patch I propose B, because honestly it's easier for my puny
mind to imagine a world where when one side sends a message the other
side actually receives it, and not operate under an assumption where
notifications are non-reliable. Keeping that in mind, I prefer call to cast.
If this is way off base please do call me out!

To remedy the performance hit, I changed the RPC endpoints on the server
to process the message with eventlet.spawn_n, following a conversation
with sileht from Oslo messaging (This pattern is common in Nova).

Surprisingly, from my very simple tests with ml2.report_device_up,
this did not make a big difference from the agent's point of view.
It seems like most of the time in a call is spent in
Oslo messaging overhead or rabbit, but not processing the response on
the server. Still, this change could make an impact on other RPC messages
or at scale. It will also let us leverage ongoing performance work in
Oslo messaging such as:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo.messaging/+bug/1437951

Change-Id: I012dfb709622b2a48705d6a999856c7ae93a7ca2

even though the recipient (Neutron server in this case) has no return
value on the RPC endpoint (Think OVS agent update_device_up). The intention
is to notify that something happened, so naturally you don't care about
a return value. In the cases I observed there is no error handling in
the agents either.

Since there's no need to wait for a response or to see if the server
successfully updates whatever it is that it needs to update, we have
two choices:
a) Switch from call to cast in these cases
b) It can still be preferable to use call and not cast to get a
   stronger delivery guarantee. Perhaps you'd still want to bug out
   if the recipient is down or otherwise non-responsive.

Note: The oslo.notify API uses cast underneath so that's not a real
      alternative.

In this patch I propose B, because honestly it's easier for my puny
mind to imagine a world where when one side sends a message the other
side actually receives it, and not operate under an assumption where
notifications are non-reliable. Keeping that in mind, I prefer call to cast.
If this is way off base please do call me out!

To remedy the performance hit, I changed the RPC endpoints on the server
to process the message with eventlet.spawn_n, following a conversation
with sileht from Oslo messaging (This pattern is common in Nova).

Surprisingly, from my very simple tests with ml2.report_device_up,
this did not make a big difference from the agent's point of view.
It seems like most of the time in a call is spent in
Oslo messaging overhead or rabbit, but not processing the response on
the server. Still, this change could make an impact on other RPC messages
or when the neutron server is busy. It will also let us leverage ongoing
performance work in Oslo messaging such as:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo.messaging/+bug/1437951

Change-Id: I012dfb709622b2a48705d6a999856c7ae93a7ca2
"}]
commit_message:
Return early from RPC call handlers with no return value

Oslo messaging reminder:
cast: Send and forget. You only get an ACK from the messaging server,
not from the intended recipient.
call: Block until the recipient sends a return value or exception.

Agents often use call and not cast when updating about certain events,
even though the recipient (Neutron server in this case) has no return
value on the RPC endpoint (Think OVS agent update_device_up). The intention
is to notify that something happened, so naturally you don't care about
a return value. In the cases I observed there is no error handling in
the agents either.

Since there's no need to wait for a response or to see if the server
successfully updates whatever it is that it needs to update, we have
two choices:
a) Switch from call to cast in these cases
b) It can still be preferable to use call and not cast to get a
   stronger delivery guarantee. Perhaps you'd still want to bug out
   if the recipient is down or otherwise non-responsive.

Note: The oslo.notify API uses cast underneath so that's not a real
      alternative.

In this patch I propose B, because honestly it's easier for my puny
mind to imagine a world where when one side sends a message the other
side actually receives it, and not operate under an assumption where
notifications are non-reliable. Keeping that in mind, I prefer call to cast.
If this is way off base please do call me out!

To remedy the performance hit, I changed the RPC endpoints on the server
to process the message with eventlet.spawn_n, following a conversation
with sileht from Oslo messaging (This pattern is common in Nova).

Surprisingly, from my very simple tests with ml2.report_device_up,
this did not make a big difference from the agent's point of view.
It seems like most of the time in a call is spent in
Oslo messaging overhead or rabbit, but not processing the response on
the server. Still, this change could make an impact on other RPC messages
or when the neutron server is busy. It will also let us leverage ongoing
performance work in Oslo messaging such as:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/oslo.messaging/+bug/1437951

Change-Id: I012dfb709622b2a48705d6a999856c7ae93a7ca2

Also, correct me if I'm wrong, but it looks like if a user this new user-centric engine then neutron's user facing APIs won't be anymore needed, is that correct?

Besides, are you aware of the groups-based-policy project? Hi, Salvatore

The User-Centric NaaS API is not to replace the existing Neutron's APIs. We think both are needed.
User-Centric NaaS API is used for the description of higher level End-to-End service requirements, which is complementary to current Neutron APIs.

If users like and familiar with such as port/network/subnet/bridge/router technology, they can use the existing Neutron's APIs to CRUD virtual network resources directly.
Otherwise, they can use the User-Centric NaaS API to just describe their E2E service requirements, which could be automatically mapped into the existing Neutron APIs. 

The User-Centric NaaS API will also be used in the E2E WANaaS blueprint for Enterprise applications or self-service subscribers to describe their E2E WAN service requirements across one or multiple domains. You've seen that BP.

I'm aware of group-based-policy project, it seems that the current GBP mainly focused on the ACL-like service policies between endpoint groups. 
I think ACL-like service requirements is just one simple aspect of user-facing E2E services.
User-Centric NaaS API allows user to describe their comprehensive E2E service requirements such as isolation, SLA, bandwidth profile, service layer/leased type, time schedule, and fine-grained value added service for user experience improvements which could be triggered by events of timers, alarms, analytics.
And user's E2E service requirements will be organized in a hierarchical way with tenant ID, service graph ID, basic service name, service instances."}, {'account_id': 14129, 'date': '2015-04-02 15:55:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-02 16:03:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

I think what Salvatore was getting at is that this sounds like it could live as a separate service plugin. Is that possible, or are there some fundamental changes that need to be made to Neutron for this to work?'}, {'account_id': 14129, 'date': '2015-04-03 01:15:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-03 01:22:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Hi Kevin,

Yes, it could live as a separate service plugin.

In OpenStack environment, User-Centric NaaS API will be compiled and mapped into the existing Neutron APIs. We will contribute codes on this.

No need to make fundamental changes to Neutron for this work.'}, {'account_id': 14129, 'date': '2015-04-05 05:56:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-05 05:58:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add availability_zone support

By adding the availability_zone attribute to agents, networks and
routers, users will be able to specify where network services run.

APIImpact
DocImpact

Co-Authored-By: IWAMOTO Toshihiro <iwamoto@valinux.co.jp>

Change-Id: Ib8ed2e7fd1a518f9199a9d3852d62a9ec604e276
Implements: blueprint add-availability-zone

commit_message:
Remove old REST to ZOOM from devstack

Now that the cluster REST API is ready to be consumed, remove the
option to use the legacy MidoNet API to go to ZOOM.

Change-Id: Ia12e4c2223057aba5ca3aa6b42b98cd9bec2e401
Implements: MNP-159

commit_message:
API: Get a subset of fields from Ports and Chassis

Since this feature is enabled for nodes we should make other resources
to consistently support this feature, so this patch allows users
to specify a list of fields that will be returned when GET'ing a port
or chassis (or a collection of those)

A small refactor was done as part of the test_port.py and test_chassis.py
to make the import names consistent across the tests modules for nodes,
ports and chassis resources.

APIImpact
Closes-Bug: #1466495
Change-Id: Id27d1322c7abf0900bfdab47a1dab59687d9b02b

commit_message:
move replication code to ReplicatedObjectController

Moving _connect_put_node, send_file, _transfer_data and _store_object
methods to ReplicatedObjectController. Each one of these methods are
specific to replication policy.  EC policy implements their own
version of them.

Of these four methods, only _store_object and _connect_put_node are
required to be implemented by the policy specific Object Controllers.

Change-Id: Ifc72461b77dbfdaae9d63417f1286e8b5da3ca4e
Signed-off-by: Thiago da Silva <thiago@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Fix the meter unit types to be consistent

The unit types for certain meters generated from
pollsters are not consistent with the once generated
via notifications. This fix handles the mismatch.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1460696

Change-Id: Ibd82fa4a5a4e66abaf2a6d0bbe18df4fbfac3ffb
(cherry picked from commit 7dfb37ea4014669f84451e6ddca3fb61872716d7)

commit_message:
Nova requires concurrency 2.1.0 or better

Nova needs the new release of oslo.concurrency in order to be able
to cleanup security bug 1387543.

Change-Id: I08693891b2b4c1d4c166e41b38adc6776e25d8e5
Related-Bug: #1387543

commit_message:
Add handler of sample creation notification

This change add a notification handler of sample.create event, which is
emitted when posting samples via /v2/meters API. The sample's info is
include in the payload of notification.

Partially implements: blueprint api-no-pipeline

Change-Id: I3941b851249c0f70f864bae32da154819b3e5dd7

[{'created': '2015-03-25 18:24:48.000000000', 'message': 'Implements integration tests for Vertica

HOWTO:
1) Get the Vertica package file downloaded to your box.
2) Checkout trove-integration.
3) Start the installation.
    cd ~/trove-integration/scripts
    ./redstack install

4) Build the image.
    DATASTORE_PKG_LOCATION=<path_to_vertica_package_file> ./redstack kick-start vertica

5) Update the following parameters to /etc/trove/trove-taskmanager.conf
    usage_timeout = 1500
    agent_call_high_timeout = 900

6) Restart the trove-taskmanager
7) Create flavor to be used for resize,
    source ~/devstack/openrc admin admin
    nova flavor-create vertica.resize 11 2304 20 1

8) Run the integration tests
    ./redstack int-tests --group=vertica

Sample Results of a test-run for:
.....
VerticaSingleInstanceTest
 Tests Single Instance Vertica Datastore.
        setUp                                                       OK  0.12
        Tests the existence of datastore and version.               OK  0.47
        Creates the instance.                                       OK  0.44
        Waits for instance to get ACTIVE.                           OK  1142.31
        Tests the restart API.                                      OK  602.84
        Tests the resize volume API.                                OK  724.17
        Tests the resize instance/flavor API.                       OK  1265.32
        Finally, deletes the instance.                              OK  181.76

.....

Change-Id: Ia8fcb14b7dd4e1f5235b15fadc0e0eeb769d23f1
Implements: blueprint vertica-db-support

    cd ~/trove-integration/scripts
    ./redstack install

4) Build the image.
    DATASTORE_PKG_LOCATION=<path_to_vertica_package_file> ./redstack kick-start vertica

5) Update the following parameters to /etc/trove/trove-taskmanager.conf
    usage_timeout = 1500
    agent_call_high_timeout = 900

6) Restart the trove-taskmanager
7) Create flavor to be used for resize,
    source ~/devstack/openrc admin admin
    nova flavor-create vertica.resize 11 2304 20 1

8) Run the integration tests
    ./redstack int-tests --group=vertica

Sample Results of a test-run for:
.....

        Tests the restart API.                                      OK  602.84
        Tests the resize volume API.                                OK  724.17
        Tests the resize instance/flavor API.                       OK  1265.32
        Finally, deletes the instance.                              OK  181.76

.....

commit_message:
Add guidance on 500 Internal Server Error

500 Internal Server Error should only be returned to a user in the case
of an unrecoverable server-side failure. It should never be returned to
the user due to a user-initiated error condition.

Change-Id: I2255ca228ac260b9b74a97df2db27b1050e54509

commit_message:
RabbitMQ container with HA support

This is new RabbitMQ container with support for HA. It's next step for
provide HA support in Kolla project. RabbitMQ is supporting now
active/active model and It's ready for active/passive model.

Change-Id: I2eb6c65f6268ee96d377e72cf880a01c8042559e
Implements: blueprint rabbitmq-ha

commit_message:
Add Neutron/Nova Floating IP create (i.e. allocate to project)

Some clouds out there are still running nova-network but we want to
provide support for neutron specific features and concepts like ports,
networks, subnets, etc.

This change is part of a set that adds neutron support to existing
floating IP-related functions, hiding that behind resource-oriented
methods.
For instance, at high level, end-users can now request that a public IP
is assigned to an instance without worrying about the specific service,
procedures and protocols used to provide that feature in the target
cloud.

Change-Id: I2196ebf9b0131346675f90ca9fb21c3baf8d177f

commit_message:
Creating action_handler to separate action functionality

 * Now it is possible to use action executions
   without task and workflow executions at all.

TODO (next commit):
 - implemeting possibility to run single action on engine

Partially implements blueprint mistral-run-individual-action

Change-Id: Ib6c20fec57ff1fd02bef5b1f9e782262309b6cd2

Use loopingcall from oslo.service

oslo.service replaces the loopingcall code from oslo-incubator so switch
to the new oslo.service module.

Well, testing this change is semi-tricky.  What you need to do is create a softlink in your .venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/xstatic/pkg/jasmine directory to the git repo versions of these files.  Here's the example on my system:  (edit to remove unnecessary garbage)

 $ pwd
/Users/mwood/Code/upstream/horizon/.venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/xstatic/pkg/jasmine
 $ ls -l
__init__.py@ -> /Users/mwood/Code/upstream/xstatic-jasmine/xstatic/pkg/jasmine/__init__.py
data@ -> /Users/mwood/Code/upstream/xstatic-jasmine/xstatic/pkg/jasmine/data


Then, when you head on over to http://127.0.0.1:8000/jasmine/ServicesTests you should see the new jasmine version of 2.2.0.


As for how it actually gets used, that will require
A) This patch to be merged.
B) Someone (Dave?) to release this is a python package onto pypi
C) The requirements.txt file in horizon will need to be updated.

So, we're a ways away."}, {'account_id': 9659, 'date': '2015-06-09 17:51:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Merge security groups tests between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges security groups functional tests.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled to run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.

Change-Id: I45bc8a6ab4b48bff6ed28b4c779b575252161ed1

commit_message:
Add pool_id param for pool_member related proxy methods

pool_id is needed for generating url of Neutron LBaaS pool_member
resource. This patch added this parameter to all pool_member
related methods in proxy layer.

Change-Id: I95b094b25f1367770de035c93c4fe88428eef8dc

Simply put, the difference between Magnum and Solum is that Magnum is all about giving OpenStack user what they need to use containers. 

Solum is about automating the software development lifecycle so that you don't need to understand OpenStack in order to deploy apps to it. You think in terms of apps rather than in terms of cloud resources."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-06-16 08:58:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I have two minor concerns with this:

* Losing steam

My impression was that Solum had lost development momentum over the past cycles, sharing its PTL with a popular project (Magnum) and gradually fading out. A bit of visibility on the medium-term roadmap on the wiki page would go a long way to convince this is not dying but really active, and would benefit from being included in the big tent.

* is a PaaS service helping with the OpenStack mission

The mission is to provide infrastructure as a service, and we ruled that things that were directly building on top of that (like Heat or Murano) were "helping with the mission" (basically by creating an ecosystem). Solum might take it one step beyond though -- building on top of Heat itself to deliver pure PaaS features.

FTR http://solum.io/ gives a "marketing presentation" of Solum for those interested.'}, {'account_id': 2506, 'date': '2015-06-16 16:39:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Thierry:

Thank you for the questions.

Solum development is very much active. We have weekly IRC meetings in openstack-meeting-alt (on Tuesdays between 4.00pm - 5.00pm CDT these days).

The current roadmap is available at:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Solum/HighLevelRoadmap

We have completed most of the features targeted for the Kilo milestone. Currently we are in the planning stages for the next set of features to be targeted for the upcoming releases.

A link to the roadmap page also appears on the main Solum wiki page:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Solum


Good point about Solum helping take the OpenStack mission forward by enabling application building and deployment on OpenStack by providing the necessary tools and mechanisms for this purpose.

- Devdatta'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-06-16 19:27:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

(1 comment)

Clearly meets the criteria for inclusion into the openstack/ code namespace, IMHO.

-jay'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2015-06-16 20:21:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

IRC Logs are here:
https://botbot.me/freenode/solum/'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2015-06-16 20:32:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Rollcall-Vote+1 Code-Review+1

We can add eavesdrop to the channel; other openstack bots are already there.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-06-16 20:42:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

I would feel better about this +1 if there was another PTL election, because the current PTL is also PTLing Magnum.

Also in looking at this I'd like to consider an additional tag of diverse:danger for projects that are more than 90% dominated by a single org, because those are very much at risk of being shut down by upper management whims."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-06-16 20:44:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Rollcall-Vote+1

I'm voting +1 with reservations related to the diversity of the team, both in terms of its active contributor base and their affiliations. I'm also concerned that the PTL for the project is PTL for a second project, which may cause communication or responsiveness issues as this team integrates with the OpenStack cross-project teams. There are ways to address both of those issues, so I don't think they should block the project from joining, but we'll want to keep an eye on them."}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2015-06-17 21:38:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

Sounds great.'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-06-22 03:10:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Some questions:
1. Your High Level Roadmap shows a lot of Heat template work dependency, yet containers seem to be the recent push. Could you better describe the container/magnum work in https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Solum/HighLevelRoadmap? Doesn't really matter for an "Are you OpenStack?" question, but I'd like to know to understand current strategy for the project. More mention of Magnum/containers integration on that page would be helpful.
2. I have no reservations about someone serving as PTL for two projects, but I would like to know how you ensure you have a backup?

I'm pleased with an app dev and deployment project, just want to understand communication and direction a bit better.'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2015-06-23 20:05:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

Anne,

> Some questions: 1. Your High Level Roadmap shows a lot 
> of Heat template work dependency, yet containers seem 
> to be the recent push. 

The work recently added to Solum for containers pertained to using containers through Heat. All of that work can be leveraged with a future Magnum integration by making minor adjustments to use the in-progress Magnum Heat resources rather than the Heat Docker resources. There is no intentional overlap. Solum started before Magnum, so it has some similar capabilities as a result. The Solum team is actively discussing how to reduce that overlap and get maximum leverage of other projects now that we have additional choices.

> Could you better describe the container/magnum work in
> https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Solum/HighLevelRoadmap?

I think you are referring to "Ability to configure Container/VM size and/or ratio (the ratio part is up for debate, but on a 1:1 we need a way for the user to configure what flavor class they need/want). I'd also like to see choice of infrastructure beyond just Nova (such as Ironic bare metal... serviced via swapping out the appropriate Heat template for the chosen deployment form factor)"

I expect this to be adapted based on what Magnum can offer, but if you use Solum without Magnum, you need to indicate how many containers it should place on each "compute" instance. That's what this is about.

> Doesn't really matter for an "Are you OpenStack?" 
> question, but I'd like to know to understand current 
> strategy for the project. 

We still maintain a strategy of minimal overlap with other OpenStack pursuits.

> More mention of Magnum/containers integration on that page would be helpful. 

That is still under discussion, but as soon as that's agreed to we will add it there. You can check the recent meeting logs if you are interested in the details.

> 2. I have no reservations about someone serving as PTL 
> for two projects, but I would like to know how you 
> ensure you have a backup?

I routinely delegate responsibility for conducting meetings to other team members. We're able to conduct project business when I'm away.

> I'm pleased with an app dev and deployment project, just
> want to understand communication and direction a bit 
> better.

Please let me know if there is more perspective I can add here.

Thanks,

Adrian'}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2015-06-23 20:47:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Rollcall-Vote+1 Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-23 20:47:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add Solum to OpenStack Projects List

Solum has achived a level of stability and maturity where all of its
contributors feel it is ready to join OpenStack. Solum's mission is to
make cloud services easier to consume and integrate with your application
development process. Adoption of Solum will lead to more application
developers using OpenStack as a cloud platform.

It is directly built on OpenStack infrastructure services including Heat,
Keystone, Glance, and Swift. Through Heat it also uses Nova, and soon
will also use Magnum.

Solum conforms to each of our four opens:
  Open Source
  -----------
  Apache v2.0 License, no dependencies restrict deployment or redistribution.

  Open Development
  ----------------
  We use Stackforge, including Gerrit for all code reviews with a test driven
  gate. The PTL is available as a liason for cross-project teams. We integrate
  with other projects in OpenStack to prevent overlap in our efforts. Solum
  conforms completely to the OpenStack development style.

  Open Design
  -----------
  Our project direction is discussed openly in pubic forums including at
  multiple design summits and midcycle meetups. We use the openstack-dev
  mailing list to discuss issues.

  Open Community
  --------------
  Solum's PTL is chosen by the community in open elections. We hold weekly IRC
  meetings in official OpenStack meeting channels.

We are OpenStack API interoperable, using keystone middleware for discovery
and authentication. We have an active team of dedicated contributors who are
committed to the success of the project.

Change-Id: Id74222381910f006a5a69f9e3746101bd4a32e12

hi Drew, just curious, but libvirt says it supports PowerVM. is this data not available through libvirt?'}, {'account_id': 8190, 'date': '2015-06-24 01:17:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hey Gordon.  Thanks for the question.  Its a good one.

The way the drivers are written are through the PowerVM API rather than through libvirt.  It is significantly more featureful by doing so as the libvirt abstraction is somewhat limited.  This provides us with more metrics than we would have had otherwise.  It is also the baseline for the work being done in Nova and Neutron for PowerVM.

Incidentally, there is also KVM for POWER.  This is sometimes called PowerKVM.  That is making use of the standard libvirt driver for KVM.

Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 8358, 'date': '2015-06-24 02:03:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Pin the oslo.i18n version for kilo

keystoneclient that is compatible with kilo depends on oslo.i18n but
it is incompatible with oslo.i18n version 2.0.0 because 'oslo.i18n'
namespace has been removed.

Update the requirements.txt temporarily to pin the version of oslo.i18n
to match what's set in Kilo's OpenStack global requirements until how
to handle library requirements is decided by the community

Change-Id: I3c9e4b863579b768f63d98677843f1570103c9dc
Fixes: MNP-160

(1 comment)

IMHO the idea of a rootwrap daemon mode is really *awful*.

rootwrap as it exists today is really offering little-to-no meaningful security protection. Opening an RPC service that just exposes root wrap command execution as a service, is more or less opening an arbitrary root shell.

If we're going to switch to an RPC based approach, then IMHO we should do it as a proper API. ie, do *not* have an RPC service which accepts random ad-hoc command line strings, but instead have an API which exposes logical functions.

ie, instead of having an API  'run command COMMMAND ARG1 ARG2 ARG2' where we pass 'losetup /some/file' to setup a loop device, have an API 'setup loop device "filename"'.'}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2014-07-08 10:06:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Unfortunately the oslo BP I'm referencing to is just about to be merged, so link to the spec is not set on launchpad yet. Please take a look at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/94613/7/specs/juno/rootwrap-daemon-mode.rst - security issues are covered there. Some ideas have been going around in the original ML thread as well: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-March/029017.html

In short, it's not RPC in the sense as we are used to know it (commands sent over MQ). It's using UNIX socket (no remote execution) and digest auth with key shared over pipe with calling process (noone but calling process can access it)."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-07-08 17:00:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the clarification. I think the Nova spec could be a bit more detailed about the way this works rather than relying on people finding the external docs to figure it out'}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2014-07-10 21:29:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Set cidr required true for create network

create a network with subnet, if no cidr is specified, the workflow
will not be able to process to next without any message to inform the
user that the cidr is required. This patch adds required attribute to
cidr field.

Change-Id: Ie29e4f6b7e6fe309c67c273f814a2c43ba36afac

commit_message:
Only use tput when we are writing to a terminal

The output of some of the commands, especially building the list of
unrelease changes, needs to be easy to pass to pastebinit. When we're
writing to a pipe, don't use tput to send special control sequences.

Change-Id: I4c8a4ffd08f362c16bbfd5ca9a47996b4f31f321

commit_message:
Produce more meaningful exception messages in nested stacks

This produces a nested exception like:
 'ValueError: resources.nested.resources.my_server: it is broken, sorry'

This re-uses the path mechanism that StackValidationFailed exception
uses.

Change-Id: Id5204c15ee96784e04522ab3c5a8e66900f9a1d3
Closes-bug: 1459837
