commit_message:
Install latest python-novaclient for integration job

This commit installs python-novaclient with an uptodate version
from global-requirements. This change should unblock liberty gate.

Change-Id: Ib353dcb5e44a5e30c46fa512d533060dc1c0bd4b
Related-Bug: #1466332

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-19 22:18:30.000000000', 'message': "Refactor ironic-install playbook to support CentOS & RHEL

Refactor the ironic-install role so that it can be used on
Centos. Also add a new template for systemd configuration so
we can install and run the ironic services.

Document the additional steps that RHEL and CentOS users will
need to take to get bifrost up and running.

Install gcc in env-setup.sh as it is needed to install pip and
we can't take it for granted.

Temporarily remove amttool from RedHat family dependencies since
it's not currently packaged for RHEL or CentOS 7. We'll handle this
in a separate patch.

Change libxslt-dev to libxslt1-dev as it is the correct name for the
package.

Change-Id: I72a5b329d3c55350644a777b5a77d61947c921bc

commit_message:
Refactor ironic-install playbook to support CentOS & RHEL

Refactor the ironic-install role so that it can be used on
Centos and RHEL. Also add a new template for systemd configuration
so we can install and run the ironic services.

Document the additional steps that RHEL and CentOS users will
need to take to get bifrost up and running.

Install gcc in env-setup.sh as it is needed to install pip and
we can't take it for granted.

Temporarily remove amttool from RedHat family dependencies since
it's not currently packaged for RHEL or CentOS 7. We'll handle this
in a separate patch.

Change libxslt-dev to libxslt1-dev as it is the correct name for the
package.

Closes-Bug: 1460930
Closes-Bug: 1456896
Partial-Bug: 1463871

Change-Id: I72a5b329d3c55350644a777b5a77d61947c921bc

commit_message:
Return timer after adding it to internal list

In some cases, its useful to selectively stop
some timers and not all. This fix allows a way
for client applications to maintain a handle
on timers and be able to stop some of them
selectively.

This is needed by
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/190842/

Change-Id: Ib258c07d6dd12ef7cc9f4a6c8cbde885048ceef8
Closes-Bug: 1466661

commit_message:
Use string for 'OS_TEST_TIMEOUT' default

Setting env variables with os.environ needs a string as value.
This fixes:

TypeError: must be string, not int

Closes-Bug: #1467880
Change-Id: Ib0c8bbf24f9d4f8926ad71773eb57c3ff41cbec2

commit_message:
Have all the looping calls share a common run loop

This refactors the looping call subclasses to share
a common '_run_loop' function, this avoids duplicating that
code and taking advanage of the commonality of both of these
subclasses.

This also moves this code closer to not being dependent on
eventlet.

Change-Id: I61c0bbd6a7cda11f96374fd7c453ac5fa89ed613

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-04 20:43:24.000000000', 'message': 'Batch add_fbd_entry calls into 2 second intervals

During an l2 agent startup, it will end up calling update_device_up
on all of its ports in a very short period of time. This results in
the Neutron server sending an add_fdb_entries RPC message for every
port, resulting in lots of messages on the message bus.

This patch batches up the add_fdb_entries calls and sends whatever
is batched up every 2 seconds. In local testing of an agent with 240
ports on it, this resulted in 240 messages being reduced to <20 without
adding any noticeable delay to port connectivity.

Change-Id: Id5b076d59f00e4f7dbcb63f4dbbed18db5a5b369
'}]
commit_message:
Batch add_fbd_entry calls into 2 second intervals

During an l2 agent startup, it will end up calling update_device_up
on all of its ports in a very short period of time. This results in
the Neutron server sending an add_fdb_entries RPC message for every
port, resulting in lots of messages on the message bus.

This patch batches up the add_fdb_entries calls and sends whatever
is batched up every 2 seconds. In local testing of an agent with 240
ports on it, this resulted in 240 messages being reduced to <20 without
adding any noticeable delay to port connectivity.

Change-Id: Id5b076d59f00e4f7dbcb63f4dbbed18db5a5b369

commit_message:
Convergence: No back-up template for stack create

Current template need not be backed up while creating a stack. With
current logic, a circular reference is created with current stack
pointing to current template as previous template.

This happens when the template is stored before invoking stack create.
The template is stored along with the stack just before invoking the
converge_stack for creating the stack. The test cases are modified to
include instrutions to store the stack before running convergence.

Change-Id: I95b629d7d42201bc8273a3f70f3e3819211b32f8

commit_message:
Use better timing mechanisms instead of time.time()

To ensure we show accurate timing information about
lock acqusition and release times use a timing mechanism
which can not/should not move backwards.

commit_message:
Merge preserve_ephemeral_rebuild tests between v2 & v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges preserve_ephemeral_rebuild functional tests.
Also verifying the response with sample file.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled to run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.

Change-Id: Id4a2f6d27bb0c1f1930186f97af208a2b20fc542

commit_message:
Remove duplicate tunnel id check in sync_allocations

Currently, gre/vxlan sync_allocations and _parse_tunnel_ranges both
check tunnel id values. This change removes the check in gre/vxlan
sync_allocations as they duplicate _parse_tunnel_ranges check and is
less fine.

Change-Id: I5827468aeaec5d6c79d469132b129aeb7da171e2

commit_message:
Stop dropping deprecated tables while upgrade in mongodb and db2

Since liberty cycle has been started tables in MondoDB and DB2 related
to API v1 are not needed to be dropped in upgrade method, that tables
were deprecated two cycles ago.

Change-Id: Ief871acc43ecab334d1708b6d32db65b65943d64

commit_message:
Fix subnet creation failure on IPv6 valid gateway

Currently a valid IPv6 address gateway of the "*::ffff:ffff:ffff:ffff"
pattern is failing due to netaddr.broadcast returning value for both IPv6
and IPv4 addresses. IPv6 has no broadcast address so the fix checks if
the gateway is the subnet broadcast address only in the case of IPv4
subnet

Change-Id: I849f95b30343d0b1c90cf91203df220bf731d8d5
Closes-Bug: 1466322

commit_message:
RBD: Reading rbd_default_features from ceph.conf

This patch enables reading rbd_default_features from ceph.conf for rbd
features configuration, falling back to layering if nothing is found.

Change-Id: Iedbd250b74c7ff191e52d0554f46504dda3568a5

commit_message:
Ignore .eggs cruft

Looks like possibly new setuptools has started leaving a .eggs
directory in the workspace. Add it to .gitignore with extreme
prejudice.

Also sync the local .gitignore with the one we're recommending.

Change-Id: Icc00208e29d3ba6d27d1626db6ab956fa286594a

commit_message:
Cleanup get_plugin_name() from the tree

It does not seem to be used since Icehouse: the patch that removed its
last usage is: 1b36e2077141749495bb32b423f3df8cbbd0eb40

I don't think we should have it as part of abstract interface for
service plugins.

Change-Id: If03f67a617efd3a7cadb96d1a86283ac14088a83

commit_message:
Create devstack plugin for testing os-loganalyze

This will allow os-loganalyze to be ran as a devstack service.
We can then run tests to make sure the wsgi app is deployable in
apache.

Change-Id: I799c346dca651628743c9b23b69f66692c603397

commit_message:
Enable all commented out tests

The first attempt at getting all the tests to work missed out the
config_overrides in the base test class and the 'role' and
'assignment' groups.

Also, sha1_mangle_key was added to encode the key before calling
dogpile's sha1_mangle_key to support all the python34 tests.

Removed the skipIf's added for py34 as the tests are now working.
Also removed the testtools from requirements as we don't need it
anymore.

Change-Id: I0e09429e6739dc946f6e15398ccb264b4d62bb42

commit_message:
Optional on_shared_storage in rebuild_instance

Today evacuate API expects an onSharedStorage flag to be provided by the admin
however this information can be detected by the virt driver as well. To ease
the work of the admin and to allow easier automation of the evacuation tasks
the onSharedStorage flag should be removed. However to keep RPC compatibility
we have to first make the on_shared_storage flag optional in rebuild_instance
function of the compute manager.

bp optional-on-shared-storage-flag-in-rebuild-instance

Change-Id: Iefdded2d36070ba2319a9bade83ba0d424548048

commit_message:
Add work around to enable heat grenade config

Because we can't dynamically Depends-On a project-config change, we
need to work around what the project config change would have looked
like in devstack-gate for live testing.

Change-Id: I52d15ed592435c0755ac1115d8bee57248aad395

commit_message:
Use list of 'affected-pkgs' from erratum in tests

Since it's almost impossible to know fixed package
version until the fix is merged, there is no sense
to list the same packages in two sections 'affected-pkgs'
and 'fixed-pkgs'. The first one contains versions of
affected packages so it should be kept, and the second
one became redundant (because versions aren't specified
there), so it is going to be removed from erratum.yaml.

Change-Id: I09614f2970ea911ba125088cf658e6da33bc8382
Implements: blueprint mos-patching-tests

commit_message:
Add possibility to disable updates repo in tests

Disable updates/security/hodback repositories on
master node and slaves if PATCHING_DISABLE_UPDATES is
True. This feature is needed for patching tests, because
it's necessary to test patches against clean GA release
environment.

Change-Id: I71d41d89d91f3622bf58d34b6b3a9ec8dbb3cedd
Implements: blueprint mos-patching-tests

commit_message:
Add possibility to disable updates repo in tests

Disable updates/security/hodback repositories on
master node and slaves if PATCHING_DISABLE_UPDATES is
True. This feature is needed for patching tests, because
it's necessary to test patches against clean GA release
environment.

Change-Id: I71d41d89d91f3622bf58d34b6b3a9ec8dbb3cedd
Implements: blueprint mos-patching-tests

commit_message:
Add exception catch in report_state for DBError

We discovered while testing Cinder in an HA
environment that transient DB errors can be
encountered that are not currently covered by
the exception catch in service.py report_state().
The uncaught exceptions were causing the thread
for report_state to prematurely exit and causing
services to no longer update the DB when, in fact,
they were still usable.

This change adds an exception catch for DBError
so that the thread can continue to function.

Change-Id: I95f79b8d6c8f5d7b3e44665306b500b8d2ce3c7c
Closes-bug: 1466991

[{'created': '2015-06-18 19:06:28.000000000', 'message': 'Optimize ipset usage in IptablesFirewallDriver

Currently, IptablesFirewallDriver._update_ipset_members() iterates
through a list of security group IDs and makes a call to
IpsetManager.set_members() for each security group ID in the list. The
problem is that set_members() is repeatedly called with the same
arguments over and over again because the list of security group IDs
contains duplicates. These duplicated calls are unnecessary because they
are idempotent.

For instance, with a security group of 50 rules created in this manner:
    neutron security-group-rule-create $SECGRP --remote_group_id $SECGRP
        --protocol tcp --port_range_min $i --port_range_max $i

Adding a server to that security group will cause 50 calls to
IpsetManager.set_members() because the list of security group IDs is 50 of
the same ID. Only one call to IpsetManager.set_members() is necessary
per security group ID.

This patch converts that list of security group IDs into a set, which
eliminates the duplicate idempotent calls to
IpsetManager.set_members() with the same arguments. This will affect
performance by reducing the amount of file locking around ipset when
adding servers to security groups.

Change-Id: Id2c8c8c1093c8abcf1fd897b23b0358aeb55b526

commit_message:
Optimize ipset usage in IptablesFirewallDriver

Currently, IptablesFirewallDriver._update_ipset_members() iterates
through a list of security group IDs and makes a call to
IpsetManager.set_members() for each security group ID in the list. The
problem is that set_members() is repeatedly called with the same
arguments over and over again because the list of security group IDs
contains duplicates. These duplicated calls are unnecessary because they
are idempotent.

For instance, with a security group of 50 rules created in this manner:
    neutron security-group-rule-create $SECGRP --remote_group_id $SECGRP
        --protocol tcp --port_range_min $i --port_range_max $i

Adding a server to that security group will cause 50 calls to
IpsetManager.set_members() because the list of security group IDs is 50 of
the same ID. Only one call to IpsetManager.set_members() is necessary
per security group ID.

This patch converts that list of security group IDs into a set, which
eliminates the duplicate idempotent calls to
IpsetManager.set_members() with the same arguments. This will affect
performance by reducing the amount of file locking around ipset when
adding servers to security groups.

Change-Id: Id2c8c8c1093c8abcf1fd897b23b0358aeb55b526
Closes-Bug: 1466921

I appreciate the effort and this seems correct to me (even that now you open DB sessions for each rule add as with the original cod,e bulks were treated with one DB transaction).

i personally would do it differently :

I would just convert create_rule to be able to either accept one rule or a list of rules (this need to be optional to not break backward compatibility, so you need checks if you got list or one rule) 
and then align everything else accordingly.
(We can discuss it further if its interesting)

create_rule can now just call the same code as the bulk code and use one transaction for bulks or one rule inserts.

But i could be missing something that you spotted (maybe return values) so i am giving this +1 anyway, just a suggestion to maybe consider.'}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-06-09 08:06:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

@Armando, thanks for your review time! Well, that wasn't a big effort though, in fact it's often much harder to review than to refactor code, as a reviewer you know it :) I was thinking of breakage but just wasn't sure about the process. We really need to define what are stable interfaces which we need to preserve and what are not between neutron core and plugins. In this case (DB mixin private methods) I'd not consider it as stable interface so "controlled breakage" does seem right to me.

@Gal, your suggestion definitely makes sense. However create_rule() calling create_rule_bulk() was one of the original sources of confusion and the reason of the bug. I personally like code to be consistent and straight forward - so bulk method calling single one seems right to me. Since we're using nested transactions I doubt we're loosing much in performance here (not even speaking that bulk security group rule creation is probably the last thing where we should worry about performance in neutron ;) )'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-06-10 01:38:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Fix callback registry notification for security group rule

Some housekeeping was done in
 - SecurityGroupDbMixin:
   - create_rule_bulk() calls to create_rule();
   - registry notification is in create_rule();
   - separate validation for a single rule and for a group of rules
 - SecurityGroupServerRpcMixin:
   - overriden methods call to corresponding super class methods;

Hopefully code is now self-documented enough

Closes-Bug: #1461024
Change-Id: Ia75d7e206716bbe74aae89e4cebd0c2c40af68a8

This is supposedly handled in the Ceilometer dispatcher, do we want that here too?'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-04-30 10:18:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

This seems like a) a good feature to have anyway b) a reasonable optimization and safety guard to control for this thing both here and in the dispatcher.'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2015-04-30 10:31:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Yeah, I have added a new filter in the dispatcher recently: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/178126/ that make it a bit more usable, but doesn't solve the real problem.

This middleware is cool because it generate a real high load on gnocchi :), but this a bit broken for the swift backend of gnocchi, but it works well with the file one for example.

The real bottle necks, are:
1) ceilometer can open 40 gnocchi http connections for send measurements (10 by workers, 10 come from the default python-requests connections pool size) 
   but gnocchi can handle only 20 connections at once by default.
2) gnocchi open 20 swift connections (10 by workers, 10 come from the default python-requests connections pool size) 
   but swift can handle only one 1 connection at once by default (5 if SWIFT_USE_MOD_WSGI=True or XXX if API_WORKERS=XXX)

For 1), I will propose a patch change the default gnocchi workers to 5
For 2), I will propose a patch to change the default swift configuration when gnocchi use swift to 'API_WORKERS=40' (yeah that looks really big) or a patch to the documentation.

Anyways, I think this change is a good idea. This middleware generated a lot of traffic on rabbit, especially with gnocchi :p.
If the deployer doesn't want to record gnocchi usage into the samples or events databases, dropping this sooner will reduce the load on rabbit."}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-04-30 16:09:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-30 17:17:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
add support to skip event/meter generation for certain projects

gnocchi is unuseable with swift backend because for every meter we
capture we are generating an event notification which creates 1+
meters, which creates 1+ event notifications, and so on. this will
flood the message queue and it will never catch up. by default, we
will configure system to ignore requests from gnocchi project.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I175c5d59529ebe51c8e5ccb379b54b05e9affe95

commit_message:
add oslo.service options

patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/194772 try to add oslo.service
options but oslo.service has defined its options into three modules,
so the right definition should be oslo.service.service which contains
eventlet back door option.

Change-Id: I1b3efe9a2e93f8548ab0d52ca10b2acf0f07d511

commit_message:
Use list of 'affected-pkgs' from erratum in tests

Since it's almost impossible to know fixed package
version until the fix is merged, there is no sense
to list the same packages in two sections 'affected-pkgs'
and 'fixed-pkgs'. The first one contains versions of
affected packages so it should be kept, and the second
one became redundant (because versions aren't specified
there), so it is going to be removed from erratum.yaml.

Change-Id: I09614f2970ea911ba125088cf658e6da33bc8382
Implements: blueprint mos-patching-tests

commit_message:
Puppet: new project puppet-openstack-cookiecutter

During last summit, it was decided during the puppet-openstack design session
that the community will provide an easy way for new project to bootstrap their
puppet module with a 'compliant' design.

A cookiecutter template was created[1], after mentioning it on the list[2] and
during our weekly meeting[3] it is a go from the community that this project
should be a core part of the Puppet scope so everyone can contribute to it.

[1] https://github.com/enovance/puppet-openstack-cookiecutter
[2]
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/064608.html
[3]
http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/puppet_openstack/2015/puppet_openstack.2015-06-02-15.00.ht

Change-Id: Iac2f76a0a5704466849cc24b50f70c64653ff932
Depends-On: I18abf0f35f2787b9252a02a9293a669ab1389319

commit_message:
Add puppet-zaqar to Puppet Modules Project

This change adds puppet-zaqar to the OpenStack Puppet
Modules project, which will contain the module necessary to configure
and manage OpenStack Zaqar with Puppet.

commit_message:
Add type:library tag

The release team is building some tools for automating common release
processes. Some of these tools will look at the type of the repository
to make choices, including skipping or including the repository or
applying different criteria or process steps. For example, changes in
library projects are not available to server projects until the
libraries are released. We want to provide an easy way to find all
unreleased changes in all libraries to ensure that they are released
in a timely manner, and that requires having a way to identify all of
the library projects and their repositories.

Change-Id: I0fb3e09e7d570acdd4a1ef8342814e824d9617c0

commit_message:
Add to_dict() to ImageMeta and ImageMetaProps objects

As we need to dictify back the RequestSpec object into filter_properties and
request_spec on the Scheduler (for having backwards compatibility with the
current filters until we change them to use the RequestSpec object directly),
we need to provide a .to_dict() method for the ImageMeta object so that we can
call it in the next RequestSpec.to_dict() method.

Partially-Implements: blueprint request-spec-object

Change-Id: I7371d5e60a33da9bbb64a6a473bcf16ea8de44a9

commit_message:
Added more devstack install  parameters to dragonFlow controller options

QDF CONTROLLER IP= (Optional, Default == $HOST_IP)
Q_DF CONTROLLER PROTOCOL= tcp/ssl (Optinal, Default == tcp) Q_DF_CONTROLLER_PORT= <port number> (Optinal, Default == 6633)

Change-Id: I9fe6ab5728b3c967902c150e0b08ba0916d19956

This can be accomplished using the following command easier (and doesn't necessitate Trove needing to support every single IDE out there):

  git config --global core.excludesfile ~/.gitignore_global

This will work on all projects too, not just Trove - just put all your own ignores in the global file"}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2015-06-15 17:07:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I believe the community decide not to use this file for IDE-related ignores to avoid 'polluting' it with an entry for every existing IDE.

You can always create your own global .gitignore file on your machine like:

git config --global core.excludesfile ~/.gitignore_global"}, {'account_id': 10440, 'date': '2015-06-15 17:08:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Interesting, TIL. Switching to -1 :)'}, {'account_id': 10215, 'date': '2015-06-15 17:13:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Here's some more links (with the same idea):

  https://bugs.launchpad.net/horizon/+bug/1253467
  http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-January/023439.html"}, {'account_id': 4240, 'date': '2015-06-15 18:57:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Yeah i dont think its a good idea to add IDE ignores to the project. Should be setup in your global ignores instead.'}, {'account_id': 16226, 'date': '2015-06-16 00:47:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks for your comments about global .gitignore.

But think about intent of gitignore and why we don't wanna add IDE files in our repo. Global .gitignore is the secondary solution if you have only one repo. Now I'm developing docker, openstack and other projects which are written in golang, python and other languages. Global gitignore is really NOT a good idea.

Please checkout nova/.gitignore https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/.gitignore

glance/.gitignore https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/.gitignore

swift/.gitignore https://github.com/openstack/swift/blob/master/.gitignore

docker/.gitignore https://github.com/docker/docker/blob/master/.gitignore

Then you will know what I'm talking about."}, {'account_id': 16226, 'date': '2015-06-16 00:56:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm an experienced git user and maintain a 1000+ stars project in github https://github.com/tobegit3hub

Adding the .gitignore file is not my own requirement, but all collaborators'. We ought to meet their requirements but not ask them to use one global file for all your projects. If you don't listen to us, just be careful not to add unnecessary files and revert the commits if you do it by accident.

Please consider about this."}, {'account_id': 5293, 'date': '2015-06-16 02:15:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Hi Tobe:

In each case (docker, swift, nova, etc) the list of files in the .gitignore is the list of files that are autogenerated by the project that shouldn't be checked back in to the repo. These are not usually IDE specific files or directories that should be ignored. For example, in the docker project's .gitignore (and I quote):
"
# Docker project generated files to ignore
#  if you want to ignore files created by your editor/tools,
#  please consider a global .gitignore https://help.github.com/articles/ignoring-files
"

Please consider a global .gitignore if you want to consider ignoring files auto-generated by your editor / tools.

Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 16226, 'date': '2015-06-16 04:09:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Patch Set 1 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-16 05:33:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-trove-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/61/191761/2/check/gate-trove-pep8/de258cb/ : SUCCESS in 2m 36s
- gate-trove-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/61/191761/2/check/gate-trove-docs/541d5cf//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 19s
- gate-trove-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/61/191761/2/check/gate-trove-python27/b4ced9c/ : SUCCESS in 8m 02s
- gate-trove-functional-dsvm-mysql http://logs.openstack.org/61/191761/2/check/gate-trove-functional-dsvm-mysql/59706ba/ : SUCCESS in 1h 23m 48s
- gate-tempest-dsvm-trove http://logs.openstack.org/61/191761/2/check/gate-tempest-dsvm-trove/ebfcdd6/ : SUCCESS in 19m 24s'}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2015-06-16 05:45:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

One should better use global gitignore as noone knows what all IDEs are there, anyone can use any different one and project gitignore would be needed to always keep adding them.'}, {'account_id': 16226, 'date': '2015-06-16 06:15:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

And can you explain why ".idea" is in .gitignore of nova, glance, swift, docker and other projects.

We don't need to add all IDE files but something reasonable. If you're making it absolute, we may need nothing in trove/.gitignore but anything in global .gitgnore which is nonsense.'}, {'account_id': 16226, 'date': '2015-06-16 06:24:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

-1 is welcome if it's reasonable. It's easy for me to add it in .gitignore locally or do in global .gitignore. But think about why I want to contribute it for trove community, why other projects have the agreement to add at least ".idea" in .gitignore, and why we should not support it but asking others to configure by themselves.'}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2015-06-16 07:49:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

So like you said, different projects have added the file, this is the actual problem, one would every-time need to have it in every project, but if you set it on global git ignore one would be relieved forever for all projects one contributes on.'}, {'account_id': 6413, 'date': '2015-06-16 11:50:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

This has been discussed before [0] and the general feeling of the community (across all projects) is not to add IDE specific files to .gitignore. IMO, that is something that the contributor should take care of. Thanks!

[0] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-January/023404.html'}, {'account_id': 15321, 'date': '2015-06-16 13:05:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 9782, 'date': '2015-06-16 14:33:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 16553, 'date': '2015-06-18 07:33:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Move _delete_port

Pluggable ipam implementation will do additional actions on port
deletion (deallocate ip using ipam driver).
Existing _delete_port code will be resused.
Moving _delete_port to ipam_backend_mixin to make this code
accessible and extendable by both backends (pluggable and non
pluggable).

This commit is a preparation step before pluggable ipam implementation
can be used.

Partially-Implements: blueprint neutron-ipam

Change-Id: If6cd623aad9e5501a26e5fb8cdecd5f55e85cd05

Use accessIPv4 and accessIPv6 if they're there

If the cloud has been friendly enough to provide an accessIPv4
or accessIPv6, just use it.

Change-Id: Ice62e9cdfe1ce7d1ea8fc0ce84de7febaa4e6c2a

commit_message:
Modify environment delete API endopoint to have "abandon" feature

Added an ability to abandon the environment, which hangs during
deployment or deleting in order to hide it from the list of other
environments.

Change-Id: Iab47cf57a7147b4fd46d3320cffa625397c6c5a5
Partial-Bug: #1438810
Partially implements bp environment-abandon

commit_message:
Apply a naming rule of GET to compute clients(q*)

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the rule
to compute clients which names are "q*".

In addition, this patch removes unnecessary str() because
all callers specify string values and we need to pass py3
tests when migrating them into tempest-lib.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: Ifbb0a0bea4bfd1e94a054e1eafcc75e443ead1bb

commit_message:
Split deployment_serializers into several modules

  nailgun.orchestrator.deployment_serializers has more than 1800 lines of code.
  This makes it hard to read and update.

Change-Id: I1d1fa22899009eaef811b1de9ad897d065a47cd4
Implements: blueprint granular-network-functions

Add Galera cluster check at the proxy level

Add Galera cluster check on port 9200 at the proxy level to know the
state of a node at any time.

[{'created': '2015-06-24 02:45:12.000000000', 'message': "Use latest build infrastructure.

Version caps on pip/pbr/wheel/setuptools are a disconnect between
the incubator and upstream infra tooling which updates everything
everytime. Since we can't do sensible deps on them (due to
setup_requires behaviour), we need to update them in advance.

Change-Id: Iaeaf5affd55e6b6ea98dc65fb64b997aa6565f6d
"}]
commit_message:
Use latest build infrastructure.

Version caps on pip/pbr/wheel/setuptools are a disconnect between
the incubator and upstream infra tooling which updates everything
everytime. Since we can't do sensible deps on them (due to
setup_requires behaviour), we need to update them in advance.

Change-Id: Iaeaf5affd55e6b6ea98dc65fb64b997aa6565f6d

commit_message:
Replaces ensure_index for create_index

ensure_index is deprecated in pymongo 3.0. It was replaced by
create_index alias.

Change-Id: I64762ba4dfb74c03e3f109374f52157181a7d1dc
Closes-Bug: #1446736
